    {
      "id": "66e72981_1bafbe1b",
      "file_path": "kubernetes/policy/values.yaml",
      "patchset_number": 2,
      "line": 220,
      "message": "I think kubernetes rules does-not allow Uppercase names and this topic names have to be in lowercase if needed to be created from Helm. https://strimzi.io/docs/operators/latest/full/configuring.html#topic-operator-usage-recommendations-str\n\nI agree with the standard topics creation, we can discuss this weekly policy meeting and get these standard topics created in the next commit where apex-pdp and other policy component charts will be included.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 7504,
        "name": "Sirisha Manchikanti",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "sirisha.manchikanti@est.tech",
        "username": "Sirisha_Manchikanti"
      },
      "updated": "2022-07-08 08:28:29.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "aeb10d22_06f6a19b",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "3f326009_d6f33765",
      "file_path": "kubernetes/policy/components/policy-pap/resources/config/papParameters.yaml",
      "patchset_number": 3,
      "line": 124,
      "message": "@sirisha, @fiachra -\n\nCurrently policy topics for dmaap for communication between components are currently unauthenticated, they go over TLS but no authentication is produced against DMaaP server.    I suppose this may be the same at least for other components as well, specially those that we interact with DCAE, etc ..\n\nThe question is, would it be allowed with strimzi to use equivalent unauthenticated topics (so no user authentication)?\n\nIf user authentication is required, what are the responsibilities at the application level, ie, java, python, etc .. do we need to add new functionality to make sure username/password is passed to the java, etc.. libraries?",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 477,
        "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
        "username": "jhh"
      },
      "updated": "2022-07-14 15:22:49.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "dd08cbb9_7fa8a19d",
      "file_path": "kubernetes/policy/components/policy-pap/resources/config/papParameters.yaml",
      "patchset_number": 3,
      "line": 124,
      "message": "The jaas.config is required to access the kafka brokers.\nStrimzi uses the KafkaUser CR to define this as a k8s secret.\nThere we also need to define which resources we need read or write access to. ie KafkaTopics\nhttps://gerrit.onap.org/r/c/oom/+/129774/3/kubernetes/policy/templates/policy-kafka-user.yaml",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 4405,
        "name": "Fiachra Corcoran",
        "display_name": "Fiachra Corcoran (EST)",
        "email": "fiachra.corcoran@est.tech",
        "username": "efiacor"
      },
      "updated": "2022-07-14 15:37:50.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "3f326009_d6f33765",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "c77efac1_2c29a635",
      "file_path": "kubernetes/policy/components/policy-pap/resources/config/papParameters.yaml",
      "patchset_number": 3,
      "line": 124,
      "message": "is it correct to assume that authentication (and other configuration) then is handled within the kubernetes realm (kafkauser cr) and it is transparent the application code?   With application code, I mean whatever goes into the docker images produced by individual components (ie. policy, etc ..).",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 477,
        "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
        "username": "jhh"
      },
      "updated": "2022-07-14 15:53:18.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "dd08cbb9_7fa8a19d",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "0ab028b7_fe07555d",
      "file_path": "kubernetes/policy/components/policy-pap/resources/config/papParameters.yaml",
      "patchset_number": 3,
      "line": 124,
      "message": "In a sense yes. The app will still need to use the correct credentials to connect to the kafka cluster and access the relevant topics",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 4405,
        "name": "Fiachra Corcoran",
        "display_name": "Fiachra Corcoran (EST)",
        "email": "fiachra.corcoran@est.tech",
        "username": "efiacor"
      },
      "updated": "2022-07-14 16:20:11.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "c77efac1_2c29a635",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "0f7b01fb_f42bf805",
      "file_path": "kubernetes/policy/components/policy-pap/resources/config/papParameters.yaml",
      "patchset_number": 3,
      "line": 124,
      "message": "Hi @Jorge, @Fiachra,\nAre there any open questions, or missing implementation for this review.\nFor the question in discussion \"Are the topics here specific to the policy components or will other services/components need to access them?\"\nAs discussed, policy-pdp-pap/policy-heartbeat are internal topics which will be used only by policy-framework components. policy-notification topic can have events notifying deployment/undeployment actions, and these notification events could be read by some other components. \nMessage router will provide access to those topics for any clients that want to use them. \nIn future components will need to access the topics through strimzi configuration.\n\nPlease let me know if i am missing anything here, else i can mark this discussion as resolved. Thank you.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 7504,
        "name": "Sirisha Manchikanti",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "sirisha.manchikanti@est.tech",
        "username": "Sirisha_Manchikanti"
      },
      "updated": "2022-07-21 08:43:48.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "0ab028b7_fe07555d",
      "unresolved": true
    },
